Title: Network Systems and Administration - Project Report\par
\par
Introduction\par
This report explains the work I completed for the Network Systems and Administration assignment. I will use very easy words. I will say what I wanted to do, how I set up the systems, how I made the CI/CD pipeline, how I used Ansible and Docker, how I fixed problems, and what to do next. I will keep sentences short and clear. This report is for someone who wants to read step by step what I did.\par
\par
1. Goal of the Project\par
The main goal was to make a small web application run on a server automatically. I wanted the code in my repository to be built into a Docker image and then moved to a real server. The server should start the web app in a container. I also wanted the process to be safe and repeatable. I used tools that help me make this work without typing many commands every time.\par
\par
2. What I used\par
I used a few tools with simple jobs:\par
- Git and GitHub: to keep code and history.\par
- Docker: to make a package called an image that has the app and all needed parts.\par
- Ansible: to tell the server what to do. Ansible runs tasks on the server.\par
- GitHub Actions: to run steps each time I push code. This helps to build the image and run Ansible.\par
- SSH keys: to let GitHub Actions connect to the server without a password.\par
- An Azure virtual machine (VM): this is the server where the app runs.\par
All tools together let me build, send, and run the web app automatically.\par
\par
3. Project steps (easy steps)\par
Below I explain the steps I followed. I show the order and why each step matters.\par
\par
Step 1: Prepare the code\par
I put the web page files in a folder called app. The app has a simple HTML page. I wrote a Dockerfile that says how to make the image. The Dockerfile tells Docker which base image to use and how to copy my files into the image and how to run the server inside the container.\par
\par
Step 2: Set up the CI/CD workflow\par
I made a GitHub Actions file in .github/workflows. This file lists the steps to run when I push code to the main branch. The workflow does these things:\par
- Check out the code from the repo.\par
- Build a Docker image using the app folder.\par
- Push the image to Docker Hub.\par
- Use SSH to connect to the VM.\par
- Install Ansible on the runner.\par
- Run the Ansible playbook that deploys the container.\par
- Check if the web app is running.\par
\par
Step 3: Create SSH keys\par
I made an SSH key pair (private and public). The private key goes to GitHub Secrets so the workflow can use it. The public key goes into the VM's authorized_keys file. This allows the workflow to SSH into the VM without a password.\par
\par
Step 4: Add secrets in GitHub\par
I added secrets to the GitHub repository. The secrets are secure values that GitHub Actions can use. The secrets I added are:\par
- SSH_PRIVATE_KEY: the private SSH key content.\par
- VM_HOST: the IP address of the VM.\par
- VM_USER: the username for the VM.\par
- DOCKER_USERNAME and DOCKER_PASSWORD: Docker Hub credentials.\par
Adding these secrets keeps passwords out of the code.\par
\par
Step 5: Ansible playbook\par
I wrote an Ansible playbook called deploy_docker.yml. The playbook does these tasks on the VM:\par
- Ensure Python 3 is present (Ansible needs Python on the remote machine).\par
- Update apt cache and install packages for Docker.\par
- Add the Docker repository and its GPG key.\par
- Install Docker and start the Docker service.\par
- Install pip3 and the Docker Python SDK so Ansible can run Docker tasks.\par
- Pull the latest Docker image from Docker Hub.\par
- Stop and remove any old container and start a new container with the correct ports.\par
\par
Step 6: Test and verify\par
After the workflow runs, it waits a little and then checks the VM's URL to see if the web page responds. If the page loads, the deployment is successful.\par
\par
4. Important details and small problems I fixed\par
I found a few small problems while working. I list them with how I fixed them in easy words.\par
\par
Problem A: Secret names did not match\par
At first, the workflow used secret names called DOCKERHUB_USERNAME and DOCKERHUB_TOKEN. My repository had secrets named DOCKER_USERNAME and DOCKER_PASSWORD. The pipeline did not read the right values. I changed the workflow to use the correct secret names. This fixed the login step to Docker Hub.\par
\par
Problem B: SSH private key error in actions\par
GitHub Actions said the ssh-private-key argument was empty in one run. This happened when the secret was not set or had the wrong name. I checked the repository settings and added SSH_PRIVATE_KEY. Then the action could use the key to connect.\par
\par
Problem C: Ansible lint warnings\par
When I ran ansible-lint it showed rules that were broken. The main problems were:\par
- Use of short module names (like apt) instead of full names. Ansible wants the full collection name like ansible.builtin.apt.\par
- Use of yes/no words that linters expect true/false.\par
- Some rules about package latest state and module parameters.\par
I updated the playbook to use full names (FQCN) such as ansible.builtin.apt and ansible.builtin.service. I also made booleans true and false. This change does not change how tasks run, but it makes the linter happy.\par
\par
Problem D: Idempotency and package version\par
A linter warned about using state: latest for apt. I changed that to state: present. This avoids installing newer unexpected versions each time and makes the playbook more stable.\par
\par
Problem E: Docker image tag handling\par
I separated the image name and the tag in the docker_image task to be clearer. The running container uses the full image:tag string like myname/htmlcalculator:latest.\par
\par
5. How I tested work locally and in CI\par
I used the following tests:\par
- Manual build: I built the Docker image on my laptop to check Dockerfile works. I ran the container locally to see the site.\par
- Workflow run: I pushed changes to main to start the GitHub Actions workflow. The workflow builds and pushes the image and runs the Ansible playbook on the VM.\par
- Health check: The pipeline waits and checks the VM URL to see if the web page responds. If it does, the deployment is good.\par
- Lint step: The pipeline runs ansible-lint. I fixed warnings so the lint step reports fewer errors.\par
\par
6. What the final system does now (simple summary)\par
When I push code to the main branch, these steps happen automatically:\par
- GitHub Actions builds a Docker image and pushes it to Docker Hub.\par
- GitHub Actions connects to the VM using SSH keys.\par
- Ansible runs a playbook on the VM to install Docker and run the container.\par
- The container runs the small web page and serves it on the VM's public IP.\par
- The pipeline checks the web page and tells me if it works.\par
This means I can change the web page, push code, and the new version will be live after the pipeline finishes.\par
\par
7. Simple list of commands used (so someone can repeat it)\par
Here are the main commands I used or that are in the playbook or workflow. They help to repeat the work.\par
\par
On the local machine to make SSH key pair:\par
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -f ./github-action-key -N ""\par
Get-Content ./github-action-key (Windows PowerShell to read the private key)\par
Get-Content ./github-action-key.pub (to read public key)\par
\par
To add the public key to the VM (on the VM):\par
mkdir -p ~/.ssh\par
echo "<public-key-content>" >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys\par
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys\par
\par
To run playbook manually from a machine with Ansible:\par
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini ansible/deploy_docker.yml --ssh-extra-args='-o StrictHostKeyChecking=no' -e "dockerhub_username=XXX" -e "dockerhub_password=YYY"\par
\par
To check web page (from local machine):\par
curl -sSf http://<vm-ip>:8080\par
